You are developing an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

All code must be written with testability in mind.
Follow this test strategy to ensure reliability, maintainability, and confidence in deployments.

==============================
TESTING PYRAMID
==============================

Priority and distribution of tests:

1. Unit Tests (70%) — fast, isolated, test single functions/services/components
2. Integration Tests (20%) — test module interactions, API endpoints, database queries
3. E2E Tests (10%) — test critical user flows end-to-end

Write more unit tests than integration tests, more integration tests than E2E tests.
Every feature must have at least unit tests before being marked complete.

==============================
TESTING TOOLS
==============================

Backend (NestJS):
- Jest — test runner and assertion library
- @nestjs/testing — NestJS test utilities (Test.createTestingModule)
- Supertest — HTTP endpoint testing
- Prisma mock or test database — database layer isolation

Frontend (Next.js):
- Jest — test runner
- React Testing Library (@testing-library/react) — component testing
- @testing-library/user-event — user interaction simulation
- MSW (Mock Service Worker) — API mocking at network level

Shared Package:
- Jest — schema and utility function testing

Do not introduce Cypress, Playwright, or other E2E tools without explicit approval.

==============================
TEST FILE STRUCTURE
==============================

Test files live alongside the source files they test:

Backend:
apps/api/src/modules/fair/fair.service.ts
apps/api/src/modules/fair/fair.service.spec.ts
apps/api/src/modules/fair/fair.controller.spec.ts
apps/api/src/modules/fair/fair.e2e-spec.ts

Frontend:
apps/web/src/components/fair/FairCard.tsx
apps/web/src/components/fair/FairCard.test.tsx
apps/web/src/hooks/use-fairs.test.ts

Shared:
packages/shared/src/schemas/fair.schema.ts
packages/shared/src/schemas/fair.schema.test.ts
packages/shared/src/utils/format.ts
packages/shared/src/utils/format.test.ts

Naming conventions:
- Unit and integration tests: *.spec.ts (backend) or *.test.ts (frontend/shared)
- E2E tests: *.e2e-spec.ts (backend only)
- Test helpers/fixtures: __fixtures__/ or __helpers__/ directories

==============================
BACKEND: UNIT TESTS
==============================

Service layer tests (most critical):
- Test every public method in isolation.
- Mock PrismaService — do not hit real database.
- Mock injected dependencies (other services).
- Test success paths AND error paths.
- Test business logic: validation rules, data transformation, access control.
- Test that correct exceptions are thrown (NotFoundException, ForbiddenException, etc.).

Example test structure:
  describe('FairService')
    describe('create')
      it('should create a fair with valid data')
      it('should throw BadRequestException when name is empty')
    describe('findAll')
      it('should return fairs sorted by startDate descending')
      it('should return empty array when no fairs exist')
    describe('delete')
      it('should delete fair and cascade delete customers')
      it('should throw NotFoundException when fair does not exist')

Guard and pipe tests:
- Test JwtAuthGuard rejects requests without valid token.
- Test RolesGuard rejects users with insufficient role.
- Test Zod validation pipe rejects invalid payloads.

==============================
BACKEND: INTEGRATION TESTS
==============================

Controller-level tests using Supertest:
- Test full HTTP request → response cycle.
- Use NestJS TestingModule with real service instances.
- Use a test database (separate PostgreSQL database or in-memory alternative).
- Test correct HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 403, 404).
- Test response body matches standardized format { success, message, data }.
- Test authentication: requests without token return 401.
- Test authorization: requests with wrong role return 403.

Database integration:
- Run Prisma migrations on test database before test suite.
- Clean database between test runs (truncate tables).
- Use seed data for predictable test state.
- Never run integration tests against production or development database.

==============================
BACKEND: E2E TESTS
==============================

Test critical business flows end-to-end:
- User login → create fair → add customer → edit customer → delete customer → delete fair
- Authentication flow: login → access protected endpoint → token refresh → logout
- Authorization flow: regular user attempts admin-only operation → rejected

E2E tests use real HTTP requests against a running test server.
These are slow — keep the count minimal, focus on critical paths only.

==============================
FRONTEND: COMPONENT TESTS
==============================

Test components with React Testing Library:
- Test rendering: component renders without crashing.
- Test user interactions: click, type, submit, toggle.
- Test conditional rendering: elements show/hide based on props or state.
- Test form behavior: validation errors display, submit with valid data works.
- Test accessibility: elements have proper roles, labels, and aria attributes.

Rules:
- Query elements by role, label, or text — never by CSS class or test-id as first choice.
- Simulate real user behavior (click, type) — never call component methods directly.
- Test what the user sees, not implementation details.
- Mock API calls with MSW — do not mock Axios or fetch directly.

Components to prioritize for testing:
- FairForm — form validation, submit behavior, edit mode pre-fill
- CustomerForm — complex form with budget formatting, multi-select, image upload
- FairCard — conditional rendering (active badge, past fair styling)
- CustomerCard — accordion toggle, conditional detail display
- Modal — backdrop close, escape key, content rendering

==============================
FRONTEND: HOOK TESTS
==============================

Test custom hooks with @testing-library/react renderHook:
- Test TanStack Query hooks return correct data shapes.
- Test mutation hooks trigger correct API calls.
- Test Zustand store actions update state correctly.
- Test auth hooks handle login/logout/token refresh.

Mock the API layer (MSW) — never mock TanStack Query internals.

==============================
SHARED PACKAGE TESTS
==============================

Zod schema tests:
- Test valid data passes validation.
- Test each required field triggers error when missing.
- Test each field type rejects wrong types.
- Test enum fields reject values outside the allowed set.
- Test optional fields accept undefined.
- Test edge cases: empty strings, extremely long strings, negative numbers.

Utility function tests:
- formatDate: valid ISO → correct Turkish format, empty → "-"
- formatDateTime: valid ISO → correct format with time
- formatBudget: "1000000" → "1.000.000,00", NaN → "", empty → ""
- parseBudgetRaw: "1.000.000,00" → "1000000"
- Test edge cases: null, undefined, invalid strings

==============================
MOCKING STRATEGY
==============================

What to mock:
- External services (database, file storage, email)
- Network requests (API calls in frontend tests)
- Time-dependent logic (Date.now for active fair detection)
- Environment variables

What NOT to mock:
- The code under test itself.
- Simple utility functions — test them directly.
- Zod schemas — test them with real data.
- Type definitions — they are compile-time only.

Backend mocking:
- Use jest.mock() or manual mock providers for NestJS DI.
- Provide mock PrismaService with jest.fn() methods.
- Reset all mocks between tests (jest.clearAllMocks in beforeEach).

Frontend mocking:
- Use MSW for API mocking — intercept at network level.
- Configure MSW handlers per test file or in a shared setup.
- Never mock React hooks directly — mock the data source they consume.

==============================
TEST DATA & FIXTURES
==============================

- Create reusable test fixtures for common data shapes:
  createMockFair(), createMockCustomer(), createMockUser()
- Store fixtures in __fixtures__/ directories next to test files.
- Use realistic but predictable data (fixed dates, known IDs).
- Never use production data in tests.
- Shared fixtures can live in packages/shared/src/__fixtures__/.

==============================
WHAT NOT TO TEST
==============================

Do not waste time testing:
- Third-party library internals (Prisma, NestJS, React, TailwindCSS).
- TypeScript type definitions (compile-time, not runtime).
- Pure configuration files (tailwind.config, tsconfig).
- Trivial getters/setters with no logic.
- Framework-generated boilerplate.

==============================
TEST QUALITY RULES
==============================

- Each test must test ONE thing — clear, focused assertions.
- Test names must describe behavior: "should return 404 when fair does not exist".
- Arrange-Act-Assert pattern for all tests.
- No test should depend on another test's state — tests must be independent.
- No console.log in tests — use expect assertions.
- Failed tests must produce clear error messages that explain what went wrong.
- Tests must be deterministic — same result every run, no flakiness.

==============================
WHEN TO WRITE TESTS
==============================

- Write tests during feature development, not after.
- Every service method must have corresponding unit tests.
- Every API endpoint must have at least one integration test (happy path + error path).
- Every complex frontend component must have rendering and interaction tests.
- Every Zod schema must have validation tests.
- Every utility function must have unit tests with edge cases.
- Bug fixes must include a regression test that reproduces the bug.

==============================
RUNNING TESTS
==============================

NPM scripts (defined in each app's package.json):
- npm test — run all tests
- npm run test:watch — run tests in watch mode during development
- npm run test:cov — run tests with coverage report
- npm run test:e2e — run E2E tests only (backend)

Tests must pass before any feature is marked complete in docs/phase-1-features.md.
